name: Chris Medland
tweet: Although it's interesting that Masi did ask the stewards for their view when he noted it, so they did have a look at the time, and were involved in the decision not to formally investigate on this occasion. But that's not the point they were just asked to decide on #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: So the stewards might think it was worthy of a penalty, but they never got asked to investigate. This wasn't asking for their opinion on the move, it was asking if the new camera angle changed anything "significantly" vs the ones available to Masi at the time. #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: To try and make it very clear, all that was decided was whether the forward facing camera provided significantly different evidence than the cameras available at the time. The stewards decided not.  They didn't judge the incident, or say whether the move was OK or not.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: It's also not saying it was wrong not to award a penalty - they're not passing judgement on the actual incident itself #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: A key point to note is this decision "is not an affirmation or review of the stewards determination made during the race, but rather is an assessment regarding whether the Right of Review exists."  It's not saying it was right not to award a penalty, just can't be reviewed #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: So this actually happened.  Wolff's reaction is: "Completely expected. I think we wanted to trigger discussion around it ... that objective is achieved. We didn't really think it would go any further."  Horner: "Obviously the right decision, it would open Pandora's box" #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: The stewards feel the footage is new, it was unavailable at the time, it is relevant but it is NOT significant.  "...there is nothing in the footage that fundamentally changes the facts..."  #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: DECISION: Mercedes request to the right of review has been denied #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: Horner says it could be argued that the footage is new and relevant, but: "Is it significant? Absolutely not."  Admits he'd be disappointed if it goes any further, and he's frustrated that it is taking so long to announce a decision.  #F1 #QatarGP

tweet: Toto Wolff: "We don't expect to gain anything from the right of review ... it's more about the principle and the philosophy" #F1 #QatarGP

name: Chris Medland
tweet: You can be 100% pissed off at the way this is playing out, but don't shoot the messenger who is just trying to explain as much as possible as quickly as possible at no cost to you.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: Max touched another car in Parc Ferme, the ISC says you can't do that. That's all it is, and that's why he's been summoned. All I did is suggest that was about to happen before it was announced. Nowhere did I say what I think the outcome should be or if the rules make sense...

name: Chris Medland
tweet: You don't have to like what you're reading, especially if it goes against who you support, but take the time to properly read something rather than be outraged at what you want something to say, when it doesn't actually say that at all.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: It's late, so I won't sit around waiting for apologies for the abuse I got from some for explaining to fans (for free) ahead of time what was about to land. I'm lucky that I rarely get abuse for what I tweet, but this thread was an exception.

tweet: @rahulbollineni I totally agree. But I was pointing out that Max had given Mercedes something to argue simply by touching the car. I never said he had influenced it, tried to, or anything like that at all. Just the facts that the video showed something Merc would use.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @GPAmericas Just to add, F1's owner Liberty Media itself said to its own investors today that it was 400,000. So there isn't a gap between their reported figure and COTA's anymore if there was before.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @GPAmericas Just on the round numbers point, like I said, they're all reported this way. Silverstone had 140,000 on race day, 365,000 over the weekend. Reported the same way. And looked like a similar crowd to COTA.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @GPAmericas Not saying you're wrong to have doubts, just that I don't see the logic in a race promoter spending more money on stuff and lessening their profit margin, all just to pretend they sold more tickets (which would also hurt their profits).

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @GPAmericas Yeah that wasn't the point, what we were told was there was more fan entertainment like that this year because they'd sold so many more tickets early on, allowing them to invest more in the trackside stuff. name: Chris Medland
tweet: @GPAmericas Of course most are repeats so in reality it‚Äôs much lower than 400,000 individual people, but that‚Äôs how all F1 races report their figures.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @GPAmericas The last point they‚Äôre just wrong to call it the biggest GP based on Sunday only. I‚Äôm not sure about the full weekend figures of Indy, but Adelaide was a four-day weekend (and bigger). The 400,000 figure is adding up sold tickets across Fri-Sat-Sun.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @EmmaKravnik I want the rules around what companies have to do to be changed, so they regulate gamblers better to prevent some of the extreme cases like the one in the video. Basically, a safety net to protect when people become vulnerable. That would be government legislation.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @hailgrabovski I agree on the first part, and on the second part it's the fact that the industry seems to take advantage of that a little. How was the lad in the clip allowed to place EIGHTY FIVE bets in one day, when he was clearly losing?

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @Lonerd Totally agree. For one, there should be alerts for the companies involved when someone bets more than a set number of times in a day (10 perhaps?) to then engage that gambler directly with a human. Or even a limit on the maximum number of bets you can lose in fixed period.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: This isn't 'All gambling is bad' - far from it. And I actually prefer self-regulation because I believe we're all responsible for ourselves first and foremost and it's a weak excuse to always blame others when things don't go well, but there needs to be a line.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: Remember that tweet I did about football and betting last week? These are the levels it can reach, because it is not regulated well enough.  Many sports gladly take the money from the industry without adequate safeguarding IMO. This clip is really painful to watch.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @makeitgood44 The thing with running was that I already ran, but it's definitely a really good barometer as you see personal improvement over time that can make you feel better. And if not, it's still just good fitness and a time people can't distract you too much!

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @makeitgood44 Yeah I used running a lot too, with music, but that was more as an inspiration. It was a good head clearer in some respects but usually it was like my motivation to dig deep and try and better myself as it felt like the low times were telling me I wasn't good enough.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @beast_246 Yup, that's the message I really want people to take away from this...

name: Chris Medland
tweet: But anything that stopped me looking at my phone tended to help, because I'd turn to it unrealistically hoping it would provide a pick-me-up out of nowhere, and then be disappointed if it didn't. Sport and people was best for that in my experience #WorldMentalHealthDay

name: Chris Medland
tweet: Two years ago I was in a pretty dark place for some personal reasons, and while the job helped distract me and some incredible people provided support, the biggest escape I found I got from it was going karting or playing football - when my mind's full capacity was on competing.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: It seems so simple, but I'm with Toto that distracting yourself with full focus on something else is really good for your mental health:  https://t.co/VkRweRcbny #WorldMentalHealthDay #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @mjd1001 Don't get me wrong, I love Daytona, I just wouldn't want to ruin it just to host an F1 race, when it's iconic for other reasons. As COTA showed, F1 sort of needed its own thing to really work, rather than jumping on the venues made special by other categories.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @mjd1001 So having done the Rolex 24 a bunch of times I don't think it would work for F1. Needs a pit lane/garage rebuild, infield is narrow and short, and not sure they could use the banking. On the sight lines, that's what Miami says the stadium will do - you can view the whole track.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @GDB_LPN I don't think so, mainly because that makes it a worse time for the European timezone (where F1 has massive broadcast deals). The Middle East/Far East races tend to be evening ones as that works well for Europe and the US.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @mjd1001 It'll be flat, but that doesn't necessarily mean boring. Not being Downtown is a shame for the backdrop/images but makes no difference to the racing, if anything more scope for a better track here. But I agree, perfect would be an epic Downtown/Miami Beach track.

tweet: I say they'll argue it, that's what Aston can still do, but no guarantees that goes ahead now.  Also, the fuel system failure was accepted as a "new" element, but not seen as relevant as the rules don't allow exceptions - you simply have to be able to provide 1.0L at any time #F1

name: Chris Medland
tweet: To overturn the DSQ using the right to review, you need a significant and relevant new element, which the stewards don't think Aston had. But to appeal the DSQ via the International Court of Appeal, you don't need that extra element so they'll argue it based on all the evidence.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @giroveloce @ecugenia What's actually been more interesting to me isn't the overall argument of the format, but more people than I expected seemed to miss out on following the competitive sessions so it didn't matter if it was better/worse as a spectacle if fewer people could follow it.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @giroveloce @ecugenia So FP2 wasn't pointless, but it wasn't communicated well. (Andrea Stella was very good saying it was really useful today), and I totally agree that pole shouldn't be awarded to the Sprint qualifying driver. Plenty of the rest needs improving, just thought Friday was fun!

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @ecugenia But the point of my original tweet was simply that we had excitement on a Friday that we don't have this week. And that part was fun.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @ecugenia That's OK, I appreciate your efforts!  I felt like Sprint qualifying was fine - I enjoyed the build-up and tension of the start - but not as good as a normal qualifying session. But we still got a normal qualifying session, which was good, so I felt overall it wasn't a bad thing.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @RoryMitchell And that said, I totally agree that the schedule could be better. But stand by the point of my tweet, not that I don't enjoy Fridays anyway but I enjoyed a Friday more with qualifying taking place in the evening - it had more of an edge.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @RoryMitchell Disagree on the P2 part - Andrea Stella made a great point today that it was still very valuable for the teams. There's a lot you can learn that isn't just car set-up (tyres, fuel management, driving adaptions etc). But I don't think we told that story very well.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @ecugenia You've just contradicted yourself a little in that tweet. Qualifying is clearly more fun than practice. Doesn't mean practice isn't still great fun to watch F1 cars, but watching those cars absolutely flat out over an hour with a competitive order at stake is more fun again.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @makeitgood44 Fully appreciate people who are working Fridays who felt the schedule didn't work (hence the other tweet about the timing) but are we saying people who don't work Fridays automatically don't have actual jobs?!  I'll let the F1 bit slide, I've never called it a real job either üòâ

name: Chris Medland
tweet: Also interesting to see how other timezones are responding to this. Seems to be the Far East where it really sucked, and not great for South America, whereas in North America it's a mix of bad (Friday) and good (later start so they're up).  Global sport so no perfect time for all

name: Chris Medland

name: Chris Medland
tweet: @SpeedNickel93 That's not what the point is at all. It's that if you don't penalise mistakes, you don't reward excellence. This is the pinnacle, it shouldn't be easy. The point is deterrents like these stop a driver pushing way over the limit and then working their way back to it.

name: Chris Medland
tweet: Perez wins the last race and then immediately gets pinged for pit lane speeding in FP1 here and Red Bull is fined ‚Ç¨1000. He was 16.5km/h over the 60km/h limit #F1 #FrenchGP

name: Chris Medland
tweet: And the point isn't "Let's see cars damaged", it's "Let's ensure there's a proper punishment for mistakes, so you reward the best skill of those drivers who can push the closest to that limit without making an error". On a track like this, with infinite run-off, it's good. #F1

tweet: @_kojo___ But it's the same on a street track. A slight moment wide and you hit a barrier. The risk v reward is down to driver skill, if you can't afford to make the mistake, you leave more margin in that corner.
